rc="https://i.imgur.com/uqOo4dT.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/U3okO1G</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[LoafofToast2012]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>This won't work (And why)</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/NG6Me6y</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/yM0cX81.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Let me preface this by saying that I've had comments downvoted twice so far, because I tried to explain this. People take it as me saying that there is no point in trying to fight this. That's not what I'm saying at all, but you have to understand how all of this works to have any chance of changing things. You can't just hope that flipping a couple of Congressional seats will do the trick. I've been in a deep depression over this because I actually get how bad it is. Please read this so that you're aware of JUST HOW BAD the leaked SCOTUS decision would be, even though it's long.

You see, it's not just Roe v Wade. It's not even the precedent this sets undermining the SCOTUS decisions on gay marriage, sodomy, and interracial marriage.

It's that SCOTUS' decision forbids the Federal government from enforcing any Federal laws on any of these subjects.

The Federal government only has the power to tell the States what laws they can and cannot pass in situations where the Constitution says it can. The Constitution does not say that the Federal government can make laws about abortion. Rather, the only thing stopping the States was that SCOTUS decided that the 14th amendment gave people the right to privacy, and thus States could not interfere in their private, personal business.

The leaked decision states that Americans DO NOT have a right to privacy, and thus the 14th amendment does not apply here. Without that, the Federal government has no power to tell the States that they cannot ban abortions.

What that means is that if SCOTUS sticks to the leaked decision, even if Congress turns around and passes a law the very next day saying that States cannot ban abortion, SCOTUS will strike down that law as unconstitutional. Even if we already had a Federal law preventing abortion bans, the leaked decision would strike that law down.

SCOTUS is the final authority on what the Constitution says in any case where it is open to interpretation. Period.

The only way to overrule SCOTUS on this would be a new amendment with clear wording specifically on the subject of abortion. Passing an amendment requires the support of 2/3 of the Senate AND 2/3 of the House, AND the President.

Without a new amendment, the only thing Congress would have the power to do would be banning the States from forbidding their residents to cross state lines to get an abortion.

This is woefully insufficient even for the abortion issue, and does absolutely nothing to change what this impending decision will mean for gay marriage, sodomy laws, and the thousand other things that rely on the idea that Americans have a right to privacy.

Unfortunately there are few options for fixing this disaster, and they're all depressingly unlikely:

1. The backlash SCOTUS is facing right now could be enough to convince them this is a bad idea and cause them to change the decision before it's published. I don't see this as likely.

2. Since even most Republican voters do not want abortion bans, we could hope that this decision is enough to turn voters against the party in enough numbers that the Democrats gain a supermajority large enough to force the passage of new amendments, and pass one either specifically prohibiting bans on abortion, and/or instituting term limits for Supreme Court Justices. This is extraordinarily unlikely.

3. We could hope that 2 or more of the conservative justices die while a liberal President is in office to replace them, allowing for this decision to be reversed. Highly unlikely given how recently most were appointed.

